["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Santo, Angelo, Matteo, Carmela, Lorenzo, Pasquale, Vittorio.","Italian (Sicily): probably an Italianized form of Spanish   Ruiz  ."]},{"name":"Ruz","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Ruiz  ."]},{"name":"Rodrigo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Elena, Rafael, Alfonso, Alicia, Angel, Araceli, Benardo, Carlos, Carlota, Cristina, Emilio.  Indian Devi, Dileep, Dilip, Gamini, Mahendra, Manoj, Sunil, Tilak.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Rodrigo</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hrōdrīc</i>, a compound of <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, kingdom’. <i>Rodrigo</i> is one of the most important Spanish personal names of ancient Germanic origin. It was borne by the last of the Visigoth kings and by a Christian saint, Saint Roderick, one of the 9th-century martyrs of Córdoba. This surname is also found in and around some of the former Portuguese territories of western India."]},{"name":"Ruis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Arturo, Carlos, Conception, Elba, Fernando, Jose, Josue, Juan, Jubenal, Lazaro, Lupe.","Spanish and Portuguese: variant of   Ruiz  ."]}]},{"name":"Alma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Relatively modern creation, of uncertain origin. It had a temporary vogue following the Battle of Alma (  1854 ), which is named from the river in the Crimea by which it took place; similarly, <i>Trafalgar</i> had occasionally been used as a girl's name earlier in the 19th century. Nevertheless, the historical event seems only to have increased the popularity of an existing, if rare, name. <i>Alma</i> is also the feminine form of the Latin adjective <i>almus</i> ‘nourishing, kind’ (compare the term <i>alma mater</i> ‘fostering mother’, denoting an educational establishment). The name was borne by  Alma Bennett  (  1889–1958 ), American vamp of the silent screen. In  Tennessee Williams's  play Summer and Smoke (  1948 ), a bearer of the name explains that it is ‘Spanish for soul’, but this seems to be no more than coincidental."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dominica","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Dominic .  This name was borne by a saint martyred in Campania under the  Emperor Diocletian  and by a wealthy Roman widow who was an associate of  St Laurence ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alma Dominica Ruiz was born in 1135, in Trenouth, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. She married Roger Carminow about 1149, in Trenouth, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 13 January 1180, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1135–13 January 1180":"1135–13. jaanuar 1180","1129–1173":"1129–1173","1155–1222":"1155–1222","1135–1180":"1135–1180","1129":"1129","1135":"1135","Abt 1155":"umbes 1155","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","Abt 1149":"umbes 1149","1173":"1173","13 January 1180":"13. jaanuar 1180","1180":"1180","Trenowyth, Cornwall, England":"Trenouth, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Trenowyth, Cornwall, England, UK":"Trenouth, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, UK":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1135–13 January 1180":"1135–13. tammikuuta 1180","1129–1173":"1129–1173","1155–1222":"1155–1222","1135–1180":"1135–1180","1129":"1129","1135":"1135","Abt 1155":"noin 1155","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","Abt 1149":"noin 1149","1173":"1173","13 January 1180":"13. tammikuuta 1180","1180":"1180","Trenowyth, Cornwall, England":"Trenouth, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Trenowyth, Cornwall, England, UK":"Trenouth, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cornwall, England, UK":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1135–13 January 1180":"1135–13 janvier 1180","1129–1173":"1129–1173","1155–1222":